Holonomy Group 101¶

$\textbf{Brief on Riemannian curvature via SageManifolds and Holonomy Group of}$ $\mathbb{S^2}$ $\textbf{(2-sphere)}$ $\textit{Disclaimer: Manuscript may be prone to errors; point them out, comment where posted and will be corrected in an errata.}$

Vol. 1, ID: 002
September 5, 2023

Introduction¶

Riemannian curvature and holonomy are fundamental concepts in differential geometry that provide insight into the geometry of curved spaces and the behavior of vectors as they are parallel transported along paths. These concepts are crucial in understanding the intrinsic properties of Riemannian manifolds and have deep implications in physics, mathematics, and various fields of science. Let's delve into these concepts:

Riemannian Curvature

Imagine you're on a curved surface, like the surface of a sphere. Even though the surface locally appears flat, it has a nonzero intrinsic curvature. Riemannian curvature captures this intrinsic curvature and measures how a manifold (generalization of surfaces) deviates from being flat.

Definition:

Given a Riemannian manifold $\mathcal{M}$ with a metric tensor $g$ that defines distances and angles, the Riemann curvature tensor $R$ characterizes the curvature of $\mathcal{M}$ at each point. It's a multilinear map that encodes information about how vectors change as they are parallel transported around infinitesimal loops on the manifold.

$R(X, Y)Z = \nabla_X \nabla_Y Z - \nabla_Y \nabla_X Z - \nabla_{[X,Y]} Z$

Here, $X$ and $Y$ are vector fields, $Z$ is a vector or tensor field, and $\nabla$ is the Levi-Civita connection associated with the metric tensor.

Holonomy

Imagine you're on a curved path on a manifold, as opposed to just an infinitesimal loop (as prescribed in the Riemannian curvature at a point), and you parallel transport a vector along the path. When you return to your starting point, the vector might have changed direction due to the curvature of the manifold. Holonomy describes this change in direction as you transport a vector around a closed loop.

Definition:

Let $p$ be a point on the manifold $\mathcal{M}$, and $v$ be a reference vector at $p$. Holonomy is studied by calculating the holonomy group at $p$, which consists of transformations that arise from parallel transporting vectors around closed paths starting and ending at $p$.

The holonomy group is a set of invertible linear transformations of the tangent space of $\mathcal{M}$ at $p$ that satisfy a group structure (defined below). In this context, the elements of the holonomy group are invertible linear maps.

Group structure:

  1. Identity Element: The identity element of the holonomy group is the identity transformation, which leaves vectors unchanged when parallel transported around a closed loop.
  2. Closure Property: If $A$ and $B$ are invertible linear transformations in the holonomy group, it means they can be realized by parallel transporting vectors around closed loops. Composing $A$ and $B$ (applying one after the other) results in a new invertible linear transformation $A \circ B$, which can also be realized by parallel transport. Therefore, the holonomy group is closed under composition.
  3. Inverse Elements: For every invertible linear transformation $A$ in the holonomy group, its inverse $A^{-1}$ is also in the holonomy group. This is because if $A$ can be realized by parallel transport, then $A^{-1}$ is realized by reversing the direction of the transported vectors.
  4. Associativity: The composition of invertible linear transformations is associative, which means that the order of composition doesn't matter.

The result of these properties is that the set of invertible linear transformations in the holonomy group equipped with composition as the group operation form a group. This group structure encodes how vectors change their directions when parallel transported along closed loops on the manifold. It's an essential concept in understanding the geometry and curvature of Riemannian manifolds.

SageManifolds

SageManifolds is the Python-based computer algebra software system utilized in this manuscript that extends the capabilities of the SageMath software for studying differential geometry. It allows you to work with manifolds, metric tensors, connections, and tensors, enabling you to explore and compute geometric concepts such as the Riemannian curvature.

Sections 1 - 5 regurgitates from Programming Differentiable Manifolds via SageManifolds manuscript. It provides the below instantiated objects:

  • manifold $\verb|M|$
  • charts $\verb|(X, Y)|$
  • open sets $\verb|(U, X_U)|$
  • vector fields $\verb|(v, u)|$

which are to be used in Sections 6 - 11 for the study of Riemannian metrics and Riemannian curvature. Skip sections 1 - 5, if you'd like to jump straight to text on metrics, Riemannian curvature, and Holonomy.

Section 1. Download and Installation (of SageManifolds)¶

Since all SageManifolds code is included in SageMath, it suffices to install the latest SageMath to benefit from the latest manifold functionalities. Supported OS systems are as listed:

  • Linux: most major Linux distributions have SageMath packages; however, it may be a version older than the latest
  • macOS
  • Windows

Having installed SageMath, if you run

$\verb|sage -n|$

a Jupyter page should open in your browser. Click on "New" and select "SageMath xx.x" to open a Jupyter notebook with a SageMath kernel. In the first cell, if you type

$\verb|Manifold(2, 'M')|$

the output should be

$\verb|2-dimensional differentiable manifold M|$

Section 2. Manifold¶

Manifolds of a given type, over a topological field, is prescribed via $\verb|Manifold|$

In [1]:
M = Manifold(3, 'M', latex_name=r'\mathcal{M}', start_index=1)
  • $\verb|3|$ integer; dimension of the manifold
  • $\verb|'M'|$ string; name (symbol) given to the manifold
  • $\verb|r'\mathcal{M}'|$ string; LaTeX symbol to denote the manifold
  • $\verb|1|$ integer; lower value of the range of indices used for indexed objects on the manifold, e.g. coordinates in a chart

Optional arguments also include:

  • $\verb|field|$ (default: 'real') field $\textit{K}$ on which the manifold is defined
  • $\verb|structure|$ (default: 'smooth') structure\type of manifold

Returns:

  • manifold of specified $\verb|structure|$ type, as an instance of $\verb|TopologicalManifold|$ or one of its subclasses $\verb|DifferentiableManifold|$ or $\verb|PseudoRiemannianManifold|$

A print statement of the manifold object prints a short description of the manifold

In [2]:
print(M)

3-dimensional differentiable manifold M

Section 3. Charts¶

In continuation of example manifold, $\verb|M|$, in $\textbf{Section 2. Manifold}$, manifolds are prescribed $\textbf{charts}$, defined as an invertible map between a subset of the manifold and a simple space such that both the map and its inverse preserve the desired structure. For $\verb|M|$, we'll prescribe a single chart:

In [3]:
X.<x,y,z> = M.chart()

$\verb|.<x,y,z>|$ are Python variables $\verb|x|$, $\verb|y|$ and $\verb|z|$, which are set to the three coordinates of the chart. This allows one to refer subsequently to the coordinates by their variable names.

Above, $\verb|chart()|$ has no arguments. Its coordinate symbols are $\verb|x|$, $\verb|y|$ and $\verb|z|$. By default, if no values passed to $\verb|chart()|$ parameter, $\verb|coord_restriction|$, then each coordinate range is $(-\infty, \infty)$.

Print of chart $\verb|X|$ outputs a $\verb|Chart|$ tuple:

In [9]:
print(X)

Chart (M, (x, y, z))

Section 4. Atlas¶

Lets define an open subset on $\verb|M|$, where $\verb|y=0|$ or $\verb|x<0|$:

In [5]:
U = M.open_subset('U', coord_def={X: (y != 0, x < 0)})

In addition, lets restrict the chart $\verb|X|$ to the open subset $\verb|U|$:

In [8]:
X_U = X.restrict(U)
X_U
Out[8]:
\(\displaystyle \left(U,(x, y, z)\right)\)

Now, lets introduce a chart $\verb|Y|$ with spehrical coordinates, (r, $\theta$, $\phi$), where r range is (0, $\infty$), $\theta$ range is (0, $\pi$) and $\phi$ range is (0, 2$\pi$):

In [10]:
Y.<r,th,ph> = U.chart(r'r:(0,+oo) th:(0,pi):\theta ph:(0,2*pi):\phi')
Y
Out[10]:
\(\displaystyle \left(U,(r, {\theta}, {\phi})\right)\)

The coordinates are now stored in Sage and may be examined via $\verb|assumptions()|$

In [11]:
assumptions()
Out[11]:
\(\displaystyle \left[\verb|x|\verb| |\verb|is|\verb| |\verb|real|, \verb|y|\verb| |\verb|is|\verb| |\verb|real|, \verb|z|\verb| |\verb|is|\verb| |\verb|real|, \verb|r|\verb| |\verb|is|\verb| |\verb|real|, r > 0, \verb|th|\verb| |\verb|is|\verb| |\verb|real|, {\theta} > 0, {\theta} < \pi, \verb|ph|\verb| |\verb|is|\verb| |\verb|real|, {\phi} > 0, {\phi} < 2 \, \pi\right]\)

Now, we may explore a transition mapping between chart $\verb|Y|$ and chart $\verb|X_U|$:

In [12]:
transit_Y_to_X = Y.transition_map(X_U, [r*sin(th)*cos(ph), r*sin(th)*sin(ph), r*cos(th)])
transit_Y_to_X
Out[12]:
\(\displaystyle \left(U,(r, {\theta}, {\phi})\right) \rightarrow \left(U,(x, y, z)\right)\)
In [13]:
transit_Y_to_X.display()
Out[13]:
\(\displaystyle \left\{\begin{array}{lcl} x & = & r \cos\left({\phi}\right) \sin\left({\theta}\right) \\ y & = & r \sin\left({\phi}\right) \sin\left({\theta}\right) \\ z & = & r \cos\left({\theta}\right) \end{array}\right.\)

And the inverse of $\verb|transition_map()|$ is set via $\verb|set_inverse()|$:

In [14]:
transit_Y_to_X.set_inverse(sqrt(x^2 + y^2 + z^2), atan2(sqrt(x^2+y^2), z), atan2(y, x))

Check of the inverse coordinate transformation:
  r == r  *passed*
  th == arctan2(r*sin(th), r*cos(th))  **failed**
  ph == arctan2(r*sin(ph)*sin(th), r*cos(ph)*sin(th))  **failed**
  x == x  *passed*
  y == y  *passed*
  z == z  *passed*
NB: a failed report can reflect a mere lack of simplification.

The reported failure for $\verb|th|$ and $\verb|ph|$ is due to a lack of simplification of expressions involving $\verb|arctan2|$.

Thus,

In [15]:
transit_Y_to_X.inverse().display()
Out[15]:
\(\displaystyle \left\{\begin{array}{lcl} r & = & \sqrt{x^{2} + y^{2} + z^{2}} \\ {\theta} & = & \arctan\left(\sqrt{x^{2} + y^{2}}, z\right) \\ {\phi} & = & \arctan\left(y, x\right) \end{array}\right.\)

Now, the $\textbf{atlas}$ of $\verb|M|$, given our prescribed charts $\verb|X|$ and $Y$ are

In [16]:
M.atlas()
Out[16]:
\(\displaystyle \left[\left(\mathcal{M},(x, y, z)\right), \left(U,(x, y, z)\right), \left(U,(r, {\theta}, {\phi})\right)\right]\)

Chart $\verb|Y|$ may be plotted with respect to the coordinate system of chart $\verb|X|$ as below:

In [17]:
Y.plot(X)
Out[17]:

Further details of the plot may be plotted through specifying the coordinates range, style, and color:

In [18]:
Y.plot(X, ranges={r:(1,2), th:(0,pi/2)}, number_values=4, color={r:'blue', th:'green', ph:'red'}, aspect_ratio=1)
Out[18]:

Section 5. Vector Fields¶

Note, the coordinate basis of a chart is accessed via $\verb|frame()|$ of a given chart:

In [19]:
X.frame()
Out[19]:
\(\displaystyle \left(\mathcal{M}, \left(\frac{\partial}{\partial x },\frac{\partial}{\partial y },\frac{\partial}{\partial z }\right)\right)\)
In [20]:
Y.frame()
Out[20]:
\(\displaystyle \left(U, \left(\frac{\partial}{\partial r },\frac{\partial}{\partial {\theta} },\frac{\partial}{\partial {\phi} }\right)\right)\)

And the set of coordinate basis of a given open subset is retrieved by $\verb|frames()|$:

In [21]:
M.frames()
Out[21]:
\(\displaystyle \left[\left(\mathcal{M}, \left(\frac{\partial}{\partial x },\frac{\partial}{\partial y },\frac{\partial}{\partial z }\right)\right), \left(U, \left(\frac{\partial}{\partial x },\frac{\partial}{\partial y },\frac{\partial}{\partial z }\right)\right), \left(U, \left(\frac{\partial}{\partial r },\frac{\partial}{\partial {\theta} },\frac{\partial}{\partial {\phi} }\right)\right)\right]\)
In [22]:
U.frames()
Out[22]:
\(\displaystyle \left[\left(U, \left(\frac{\partial}{\partial x },\frac{\partial}{\partial y },\frac{\partial}{\partial z }\right)\right), \left(U, \left(\frac{\partial}{\partial r },\frac{\partial}{\partial {\theta} },\frac{\partial}{\partial {\phi} }\right)\right)\right]\)

Thus, vector fields of a given open subset may be defined via $\verb|vector_field()|$ of a given open subset with respect to one of the given coordinate basis. If no coordinate basis is specified, it will be defined with respect to the default coordinate basis:

In [23]:
v = U.vector_field(1+y, -x, x*y*z, name='v')
v.display()
Out[23]:
\(\displaystyle v = \left( y + 1 \right) \frac{\partial}{\partial x } -x \frac{\partial}{\partial y } + x y z \frac{\partial}{\partial z }\)

Once vector fields are instantiated, the parent tangent space object is accessed via $\verb|parent()|$ of vector field object:

In [24]:
v.parent()
Out[24]:
\(\displaystyle \mathfrak{X}\left(U\right)\)

The set $\verb|(U)|$ above is a free module over the commutative algebra $C^{\infty}(U)$ of vector fields on $\verb|U|$:

In [25]:
print(v.parent())

Free module X(U) of vector fields on the Open subset U of the 3-dimensional differentiable manifold M

A change of coordinate basis for a vector field may be prescribed via passing a valid coordinate basis of interest:

In [26]:
v.display(Y.frame(), Y)
Out[26]:
\(\displaystyle v = \left( r^{3} \cos\left({\phi}\right) \cos\left({\theta}\right)^{2} \sin\left({\phi}\right) \sin\left({\theta}\right)^{2} + \cos\left({\phi}\right) \sin\left({\theta}\right) \right) \frac{\partial}{\partial r } + \left( -\frac{r^{3} \cos\left({\phi}\right) \cos\left({\theta}\right) \sin\left({\phi}\right) \sin\left({\theta}\right)^{3} - \cos\left({\phi}\right) \cos\left({\theta}\right)}{r} \right) \frac{\partial}{\partial {\theta} } + \left( -\frac{r \sin\left({\theta}\right) + \sin\left({\phi}\right)}{r \sin\left({\theta}\right)} \right) \frac{\partial}{\partial {\phi} }\)

The expanded tensor field terms may be accessed with respect to a change of coordinate basis via $\verb|display_comp()|$ with the coordinate basis and chart passed to the first argument and second argument, respectively:

In [27]:
v.display_comp(Y.frame(), Y)
Out[27]:
\(\displaystyle \begin{array}{lcl} v_{\phantom{\, r}}^{ \, r } & = & r^{3} \cos\left({\phi}\right) \cos\left({\theta}\right)^{2} \sin\left({\phi}\right) \sin\left({\theta}\right)^{2} + \cos\left({\phi}\right) \sin\left({\theta}\right) \\ v_{\phantom{\, {\theta}}}^{ \, {\theta} } & = & -\frac{r^{3} \cos\left({\phi}\right) \cos\left({\theta}\right) \sin\left({\phi}\right) \sin\left({\theta}\right)^{3} - \cos\left({\phi}\right) \cos\left({\theta}\right)}{r} \\ v_{\phantom{\, {\phi}}}^{ \, {\phi} } & = & -\frac{r \sin\left({\theta}\right) + \sin\left({\phi}\right)}{r \sin\left({\theta}\right)} \end{array}\)

Now to specify a vector field with undefined function (scalar field) components, utilize SageMath symbolic $\verb|function|$ object to specify the undefined functions per term:

In [28]:
u = U.vector_field(name='u')
u[:] = [function('u_x')(x,y,z), function('u_y')(x,y,z), function('u_z')(x,y,z)]
u.display()
Out[28]:
\(\displaystyle u = u_{x}\left(x, y, z\right) \frac{\partial}{\partial x } + u_{y}\left(x, y, z\right) \frac{\partial}{\partial y } + u_{z}\left(x, y, z\right) \frac{\partial}{\partial z }\)

Section 6. Metric Structures¶

Riemmanian metrics are instantiated via $\verb|riemannian_metric()|$ for a given manifold:

In [29]:
g = M.riemannian_metric('g')
print(g)

Riemannian metric g on the 3-dimensional differentiable manifold M

The Riemannian metric is a type-(0,2) symmetric tensor field on a given manifold $\mathcal{M}$:

In [30]:
g.parent()
Out[30]:
\(\displaystyle \mathcal{T}^{(0, 2)}\left(\mathcal{M}\right)\)
In [31]:
print(g.parent())

Free module T^(0,2)(M) of type-(0,2) tensors fields on the 3-dimensional differentiable manifold M
In [32]:
g.symmetries()

symmetry: (0, 1); no antisymmetry

The Riemmanian metric may be defined through assigning coefficients to its respective components via $\verb|[]|$ operator:

In [33]:
g[1,1], g[2,2], g[3,3] = 1, 1, 1
g.display()
Out[33]:
\(\displaystyle g = \mathrm{d} x\otimes \mathrm{d} x+\mathrm{d} y\otimes \mathrm{d} y+\mathrm{d} z\otimes \mathrm{d} z\)

The metric may be displayed with respect to another coordinate system via passing the chart frame to the metric's $\verb|display()|$ function:

Section 11. Holonomy Group of $\mathbb{S^2}$¶

Since parallel transport, a way of transporting geometrical vectors/data along smooth curves in a manifold, preserves the Riemannian metric, the holonomy group is contained in the orthogonal group O(n). Moreover, if the manifold is orientable, then it is contained in the special orthogonal group. A generic Riemannian metric on an orientable manifold has holonomy group SO(n), but for some special metrics it can be a subgroup, in which case the manifold is said to have special holonomy.

Below we analyze the holonomy group of $\mathbb{S^2}$ as derived in Geometry, Topology, Physics by Mikio Nakahara (Example 7.7):

First, suppose the initial vector is:

In [70]:
X0 = S2.vector_field(1, 0)
X0.display()
Out[70]:
\(\displaystyle \frac{\partial}{\partial \theta }\)

and we aim to parallel transport along $0 \le \phi \le 2\pi$ and $\theta = \theta_0$ of our $\verb|S2|$ 2-sphere.

Note, a vector field on our 2-sphere object, $\verb|S2|$, is defined as:

In [71]:
ph, th = S2.atlas()[0][0], S2.atlas()[0][1]
X = S2.vector_field(function('X_theta')(th,ph), function('X_phi')(th,ph), name='X')
In [72]:
X.display()
Out[72]:
\(\displaystyle X = X_{\theta}\left(\theta, \phi\right) \frac{\partial}{\partial \theta } + X_{\phi}\left(\theta, \phi\right) \frac{\partial}{\partial \phi }\)

where $X_{\theta}$ is the theta component of $X$, $X_{\phi}$ is the phi component of $X$, $0 \le \phi \le 2\pi$ and $\theta = \theta_0$.

Then, we apply a parallel transport action on $\verb|X|$ using the Levi-Cevita connection $\verb|nabla|$:

In [73]:
nabla(X).display()
Out[73]:
\(\displaystyle \nabla_{g} X = \frac{\partial\,X_{\theta}}{\partial \theta} \frac{\partial}{\partial \theta }\otimes \mathrm{d} \theta + \left( -X_{\phi}\left(\theta, \phi\right) \cos\left(\theta\right) \sin\left(\theta\right) + \frac{\partial\,X_{\theta}}{\partial \phi} \right) \frac{\partial}{\partial \theta }\otimes \mathrm{d} \phi + \left( \frac{X_{\phi}\left(\theta, \phi\right) \cos\left(\theta\right) + \sin\left(\theta\right) \frac{\partial\,X_{\phi}}{\partial \theta}}{\sin\left(\theta\right)} \right) \frac{\partial}{\partial \phi }\otimes \mathrm{d} \theta + \left( \frac{X_{\theta}\left(\theta, \phi\right) \cos\left(\theta\right) + \sin\left(\theta\right) \frac{\partial\,X_{\phi}}{\partial \phi}}{\sin\left(\theta\right)} \right) \frac{\partial}{\partial \phi }\otimes \mathrm{d} \phi\)

where $0 \le \phi \le 2\pi$ and $\theta = \theta_0$.

In matrix form:

In [74]:
nabla(X)[:]
Out[74]:
\(\displaystyle \left(\begin{array}{rr} \frac{\partial\,X_{\theta}}{\partial \theta} & -X_{\phi}\left(\theta, \phi\right) \cos\left(\theta\right) \sin\left(\theta\right) + \frac{\partial\,X_{\theta}}{\partial \phi} \\ \frac{X_{\phi}\left(\theta, \phi\right) \cos\left(\theta\right) + \sin\left(\theta\right) \frac{\partial\,X_{\phi}}{\partial \theta}}{\sin\left(\theta\right)} & \frac{X_{\theta}\left(\theta, \phi\right) \cos\left(\theta\right) + \sin\left(\theta\right) \frac{\partial\,X_{\phi}}{\partial \phi}}{\sin\left(\theta\right)} \end{array}\right)\)

Note, that for components $\verb|nabla(X)[1,2]|$ and $\verb|nabla(X)[2,2]|$

$-X_{\phi}(\theta,\phi)cos(\theta)sin(\theta) + \frac{\partial X_{\theta}}{\partial\phi} = 0$

and

$\frac{X_{\theta}(\theta,\phi)cos(\theta) + sin(\theta)\frac{\partial X_{\phi}}{\partial\phi}}{sin(\theta)} = X_{\theta}(\theta,\phi)cot(\theta) + \frac{\partial X_{\phi}}{\partial\phi} = 0$.

Again, $0 \le \phi \le 2\pi$ and $\theta = \theta_0$. Furthermore, the above are expressions of harmonic oscillators.

Now, lets solve for $X_{\theta}$ and $X_{\phi}$. First, take the partial derivative of component $\verb|nabla(X)[1,2]|$ with respect to $\phi$ and substitute $\verb|nabla(X)[2,2]|$ into the expression:

In [75]:
nabla_X_12 = nabla(X)[1,2]
del_nabla_X_12 = nabla_X_12.derivative(ph)
del_nabla_X_12
Out[75]:
\(\displaystyle -\cos\left(\theta\right) \sin\left(\theta\right) \frac{\partial\,X_{\phi}}{\partial \phi} + \frac{\partial^2\,X_{\theta}}{\partial \phi ^ 2}\)
In [76]:
pde = -function('X_theta')(th,ph) * cos(th)^2 + diff(diff(function('X_theta')(th,ph), ph), ph)
pde
Out[76]:
\(\displaystyle -X_{\theta}\left(\theta, \phi\right) \cos\left(\theta\right)^{2} + \frac{\partial^{2}}{(\partial \phi)^{2}}X_{\theta}\left(\theta, \phi\right)\)

Hence, a general solution for $\verb|pde|$ where $\verb|pde = 0|$ is $X_{\theta} = A*cos (C_{\theta}*\phi) + B*sin(C_{\theta}*\phi)$, where $C_{\theta} = cos(\theta)$, $0 \le \phi \le 2\pi$, and $\theta = \theta_0$.

At $\phi = 0$, $X_\theta = 1$, given that $X_0 = \frac{\partial}{\partial\theta}$. Hence, a solution that satisfies the given initial condition is $X_{\theta} = cos(C_{\theta}*\phi)$. By further deduction, $X_{\phi} = \frac{sin(C_{\theta}*\phi)}{sin(\theta)}$, where $0 \le \phi \le 2\pi$ and $\theta = \theta_0$. Thus, following a full parallel transport around the circle at $\theta = \theta_0$:

$X(\phi = 2\pi) = \frac{sin(C_{\theta}*2\pi)}{sin(\theta)}\frac{\partial}{\partial\phi} + cos(C_{\theta}*2\pi)\frac{\partial}{\partial\theta}$.

In conclusion, the full parallel transport of vector $X$, starting from a point $p$ and back, equates to a $C_{\theta}*2\pi$ rotation at point $p$, where $C_{\theta} = cos(\theta)$ and $\theta = \theta_0$. The same analysis can be applied to any point $p$ on $\mathbb{S^2}$. Furthermore, in addition to the rotations observed via parallel transport, the parallel transport preserves the metric and $\mathbb{S^2}$ is orientable. Thus, the holonomy group is a special orthogonal group of $SO(2)$.

Appendix¶

Software Architecture - SageManifolds¶

From a computer architectural perspective, SageManifolds can be described as follows:

  1. Language and Environment: SageManifolds is developed using the Python programming language and is designed to work within the SageMath environment. SageMath provides a powerful computational environment for mathematical calculations and integrates several libraries, including SymPy for symbolic mathematics.

  2. Object-Oriented Design: SageManifolds adopts an object-oriented design approach, representing mathematical entities such as manifolds, charts, differential forms, and maps as objects with associated methods and properties. This design allows for modular and extensible code organization, enabling easy manipulation and computation on these objects, alongside encapsulation of data and functionality, and the ability to define relationships and hierarchies among objects.

  3. Manifold Representation: Manifolds in SageManifolds are represented using data structures that capture their essential properties. A manifold object contains information such as the manifold's dimension, name, coordinate charts, and associated differential structures. These structures are typically implemented as classes and utilize data structures like lists, dictionaries, and arrays.

  4. Chart Representation: Coordinate charts on manifolds are represented as objects, storing information about the chart's domain, range, coordinate systems, and transition maps. SageManifolds provides classes to handle different types of coordinate systems, such as Cartesian coordinates, polar coordinates, or other user-defined coordinate systems.

  5. Differential Forms and Maps: SageManifolds provides classes to represent differential forms and maps between manifolds. Differential forms are represented as linear combinations of basis forms, with operations defined for addition, multiplication, and differentiation. Maps between manifolds are represented using DiffMap objects, storing the expressions defining the map and providing methods for composition, pushforward, and pullback.

  6. Symbolic and Numerical Computation: SageManifolds leverages the capabilities of the underlying SageMath environment for both symbolic and numerical computation. It utilizes SymPy for symbolic mathematics, allowing users to work with expressions, perform algebraic manipulations, and compute derivatives symbolically. Numerical computations can be performed using numerical libraries integrated into SageMath, such as NumPy and SciPy.

  7. Integration with SageMath: SageManifolds is seamlessly integrated into the SageMath environment, which provides a wide range of mathematical functionality. Users can access SageMath's extensive library of mathematical functions, algorithms, and tools to complement their work with SageManifolds. This integration allows for a comprehensive mathematical environment that supports various mathematical disciplines.

  8. Extensibility: SageManifold is designed to be extensible, allowing users to define their own mathematical objects, functions, and algorithms. It provides a framework for creating new classes, extending existing functionality, and contributing new features to the software.

  9. Computational Efficiency: SageManifold incorporates currently known efficient algorithms and data structures to ensure computational efficiency. It optimizes operations and algorithms, utilizes parallel processing when possible, and integrates specialized libraries for specific mathematical computations.

  10. Cross-Platform Compatibility: SageManifold is designed to be cross-platform, supporting major operating systems such as Windows, macOS, and Linux. This compatibility allows users to access SageManifold's functionalities on their preferred operating systems without limitations.

Overall, SageManifolds combines the power of symbolic mathematics, object-oriented design, and computational libraries to provide a robust and flexible framework for working with smooth manifolds and differential forms. Its architectural design enables efficient representation, manipulation, and computation of mathematical objects, making it a valuable tool for researchers and practitioners in the field of differential geometry and related disciplines.
